@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "HTML and CSS";
}

<div class="container">
    <h1>All Websites Use <span class="highlight-red">HTML</span> and <span class="highlight-red">CSS</span></h1>

    <p>
        <span class="highlight-red">HTML</span> – <strong>Hypertext Markup Language</strong><br />
        &bull; <em>not a programming language</em><br />
        &bull; consists of <strong>HTML <span class="highlight-red">elements</span></strong> called <strong><span class="highlight-red">tags</span></strong> or
        <strong><span class="highlight-marker">markers</span></strong><br />
        &bull; these <span class="highlight-red">tags</span> instruct web browsers how to render the web page structure<br />
        &bull; HTML documents are stored as text files with the extension <strong><span class="highlight-ext">.html</span></strong> or <strong><span class="highlight-ext">.htm</span></strong>
    </p>

    <p>
        <span class="highlight-red">CSS</span> – <strong>Cascading Style Sheets</strong><br />
        &bull; is a presentation language created to style the appearance of content<br />
        &bull; CSS should not be written inside of an HTML document and vice versa<br />
        <strong><span class="highlight-rule">As a rule, HTML will always represent content, and CSS will always represent the appearance of that content.</span></strong>
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>More Advanced Technologies</h2>
    <p>
        Larger websites often make use of more complex technologies on the web server:<br />
        &bull; usage of a <strong>database</strong> to store data<br />
        &bull; <strong>programming languages</strong> such as PHP, ASP.Net, Java, or Ruby…<br />
        &bull; these technologies are actually used to produce HTML and CSS that is then sent to the browser
    </p>

    <div class="navigation-buttons">
        <a href="@Url.Action("NextTopic", "WebBasics")" class="btn btn-primary">Next &raquo;</a>
    </div>
</div>

